snippet.textDisplay:
Fun fact: nowadays in Robin Hood, it's fairly common for Robin to have a saracen character included in his team (not always, I think the Ridley Scott's movie from was it 2010 doesn't have one, but like), but their characterisations vary even more wildly than most others'; Prince of Thieves has the guy follow Robin because Robin saved his life so he feels obligated to follow him until he can somehow pay back that debt, in the BBC tv show it's a woman who starts out disguised as a guy for some reason, whereas the newest (was it 2019 or 2018?) movie adaptation apparently fuses the saracen character with Little John.

You'll also notice, if you look into it, that the saracen character doesn't appear in any old ballads, or novels, or even in the early movie adaptations. The first appearance of a saracen outlaw in Robin Hood is in the 1984-1986 fantasy show Robin of Sherwood (btw I wouldn't be surprised if some of the association of Robin Hood with paganism came from RoS, as that show drew heavily from celtic folklore and overall threw straight-up fantasy elements into the mix, which isn't that common in Robin Hood). He's Nasir, he's an ex-assassin, his backstory is kinda complicated. Originally he wasn't even meant to become a regular character or a good guy, but just a minion to the one-off villain in the show's first story, that Robin would kill near the end. He didn't even have any lines. But the actor was pretty close in age to the outlaws' actors, and they became pretty good friends during filming, (and apparently some of the women of the shooting crew thought that Mark Ryan looked pretty hot, and mentioned this to the writer) so the writer decided to have Robin spare Nasir's life, and have Nasir become one of the outlaws.

So the saracen outlaw is a very new character in Robin Hood. But unlike a lot of the characters one adaptation or another adds to the outlaws, the saracen stuck. He was actually popularised by Robin Hood Prince of Thieves, which... overall has been accused of ripping off of Robin of Sherwood, but since I haven't seen the movie, I don't know if that accusation has any point. Either way, in the case of the saracen outlaw, Prince of Thieves very nearly strayed into the realm of copyright violations. Story goes, the writer and director of the movie had seen Robin of Sherwood back when it had aired, and had liked it, but neither had ever realized Nasir was an original character of the show, not an older part of the lore. It was only when the stunt director of the movie (who had also worked as stunt director and stuntman in RoS) saw the script that anyone noticed the mistake. Which was then corrected by quickly changing the character's name from Nasir to whatever they actually used for him in the final movie.

After Prince of Thieves, the saracen character stuck around, but due to it being such a new addition, its name and backstory vary a lot (and apparently even gender isn't fixed, judging by the BBC adaptation).


Also btw, I'm pretty sure Robin of Sherwood was also one of the earliest, if not the earliest, adapation where King Richard was portrayed as sucking just as bad as his brother. (He also appeared in like exactly one episode, and then went off to Normandy to fight another war, and in one episode next season it was mentioned he'd died there offscreen, making John, who continued appearing throughout the rest of the show, the king.)

snippet.textDisplay:
Capitalism is a natural evolution of barting. And as long as 1 person is smarter than another, they will come out with more than an equal value. Sure, on the extremes, it's extreme. But for most folks in the center capitalism is good enough.
As opposed to taking everything from the people who have it and pretending to spread it around.

As for the claim it's archaic, that implies its not blindingly simple. We use some kind of Thing (see money) to act as a separate thing to barter with, as opposed to raw material goods swapping hands. If anything, having the Thing helps keep it from being to unbalanced, otherwise 1 person would claim some rare resource and not accept any trades outside of ones that heavily favor them.
And as for being designed to keep some people at the bottom, I'd ask what in the structure does that? The idea of having something to trade that isn't raw goods? Wouldn't that just keep down anyone down where they don't have a means to obtain some raw good to trade? And if it's provided for them, who has to make it? Aren't they being kept down from having more materals by being forced to distribute them?

Capitalism isn't this idea made by people who got together and were out to actively hurt another group. Its was probably more like "how do we make trading simpler?" "Well, lets use a Thing that is worth a set amount of this other thing we all like, like a shell being worth so much rice/grain/etc."

So sure, it's unfair. But so is litterally everything else on the planet. Whats the alternative, push everyone so far down that they are all at zero? What about the people who DO get up at 5AM and don't get to sleep till 11PM, working to make steel rebar. Do they just have to suck it up and suffer in silence so that so hipster can say they deserve to use that metal to make homes that get wrecked and need rebuilt because they want to live on a fault line? And what should they do? No Capitalism, then being a writer, artist, influencer, Youtuber, whatever, wouldn't help anyone at all, so should they be helped as much as a famer takijg care of his children?

It seems to me the only argument agaisnt capitalism is that it's not easy, and some people are a lot better at it, and have a leg up. But that's still better than no one getting anywhere, and everyone having the boot of the collective on their neck to keep them in place.
But it's life, if it was easy, they would call it easy, not life.

snippet.textDisplay: The near complete absence of plot in Robin Hood, as opposed to a huge chunk of iconic setting, is probably one reason why the most recent Robin Hood adaptations (the Russel Crowe one and the Taron Egerton one) are origin stories that end with Robin and his gang fleeing authority to Sherwood forest, cutting the story off once the familiar setting is established. That coupled with an unnecessarily complicated plot by the villains to seize power in England, when really a simple story about a trickster redistributing some wealth with a cheeky grin would probably be more enjoyable.

It's rather neat to learn the various versions of him, especially the one where Maid Marion bests him and his amusingly screwed up ends. It's more amusing still, however, to realize that for some reason, the best two of the most recent incarnations of the characters are the two most whimsical ones, with one being the intentionally silly Men in Tights and one being the furry Disney version. Meanwhile, the four--five?--overall most recent takes have all been immensely serious, "realistic" gritty affairs that still manage somehow be more anachronistic overall in their lavish set-pieces and lackluster plots while also being far more boring despite intentionally trying to be far more action-packed.

Honestly Red I disagree with you, the system in robin hood is feudalism not capitalism. capitalism works in that, by virtue of personal freedom, the only way to get richer is to give someone else something they want, making the who is the most successful is the one who does the most good, provided peoples rights are protected indicriminately. Feudalism on the other hand is the opposite, the idea that a lord says "you work for me or either I or someone else will kill you" it fundamentally disrespects the rights and personal freedom of it's people and thereby makes the most successful person the one who can oppress the most people.


Feudalism sucks.








As a sidenote donating to charity is part of capitalism, people are free to use their money to help other people, instead of being forced to pay money that noone is able to use.

snippet.textDisplay: I once read somewhere that the English have kept a love of Robin Hood thanks in part to pre-Norman conquest view of outlaws. They were usually outlawed for a period of time for a petty crime or something that got them banished for a bit, but with the assumption that they could come home afterwards (usually). Also, with all the political shenanigans of conquest, trade, re-conquered, Vikings, etc., putting a giant middle finger to power was basically an English human right. Which translates pretty well for Americans. (Terry Cook's "Mideival Lives", I think was the book.)

snippet.textDisplay: Hi Overly Sarcastic Productions here's a new idea for your Legends Summarized: Why not do ''Ivanhoe'' it take place in 12th-century England with colorful descriptions of a tournament, outlaws, a witch trail and divisions between Jews and Christians. It also shows important influence on popular perceptions of Robin Hood, Richard the Lionheart, and King John(since you mentioned about him and Sir Walter Scott, plus this genre has historical novel and chivalric romance). Or how about "A Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court" by Samuel Langhorne Clemens AKA Mark Twain. It is a satire of feudalism and monarchy that also celebrates homespun ingenuity and democratic values while questioning the ideals of capitalism and outcomes of the Industrial Revolution(plus this genre has humor, satire, alternate history, science fiction AKA time travel, and fantasy too!)
snippet.textOriginal: Hi Overly Sarcastic Productions here's a new idea for your Legends Summarized: Why not do ''Ivanhoe'' it take place in 12th-century England with colorful descriptions of a tournament, outlaws, a witch trail and divisions between Jews and Christians. It also shows important influence on popular perceptions of Robin Hood, Richard the Lionheart, and King John(since you mentioned about him and Sir Walter Scott, plus this genre has historical novel and chivalric romance). Or how about "A Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court" by Samuel Langhorne Clemens AKA Mark Twain. It is a satire of feudalism and monarchy that also celebrates homespun ingenuity and democratic values while questioning the ideals of capitalism and outcomes of the Industrial Revolution(plus this genre has humor, satire, alternate history, science fiction AKA time travel, and fantasy too!)
